{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca94e7ff-2eda-4630-be87-21603c2890a1","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool=true` | Tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — stdio MCP servers must be executable |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # starts the stdio MCP server\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. Want me to scaffold the actual project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d7db13d-0814-4575-ba76-b95e808800b3","outputTokens":505},"id":"00179518-39b7-4b50-8aac-a39e6dc32800","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:36.246Z","parentId":"00ecaaa2-0568-444f-9670-4c45ce695bb6"}
